I – Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Definition

Clients should not be forced to implement methods they do not use.

Better to create small interfaces than one large interface.

Bad Example
interface Worker {

    void work();

    void eat();
}

Robot does not eat.

class Robot implements Worker {

    public void work() {
    }

    public void eat() {
        // unnecessary
    }
}

Violation of ISP.

Good Example
interface Workable {
    void work();
}

interface Eatable {
    void eat();
}

Human:

class Human implements Workable, Eatable {

    public void work() {
    }

    public void eat() {
    }
}

Robot:

class Robot implements Workable {

    public void work() {
    }
}
Real-Life Example

Printer

Simple printer:

Print

Advanced printer:

Print
Scan
Fax

Simple printer shouldn't implement scan() and fax().

Benefits

✔ Smaller interfaces

✔ Reduced dependencies

✔ More flexibility